│ result: `select i1 %cmp, i32 %ct, i32 123`\n- When `%x = 0`, the cttz call with `is_zero_poison = false` returns 32 (the bit width)\n- The select correctly chooses the else branch (123) │
│ because `%cmp` is false when `%x = 0`\n\nAfter the transformation:\n- The icmp becomes `icmp eq i32 %x, 0` \n- The select operands are swapped due to `freelyInvertAllUsersOf`\n-         │
│ However, there's a critical problem: during the same optimization pass, the cttz intrinsic's second parameter gets changed from `false` to `true`\n\nLooking at the opt log, we see two   │
│ iterations:\n- Iteration 1: Adds range metadata to cttz and canonicalizes the icmp\n- Iteration 2: Changes cttz's is_zero_poison parameter from false to true\n\nWhen `is_zero_poison`    │
│ becomes true, calling cttz with `%x = 0` produces poison, which causes UB when the select tries to use it (even though the select should choose the other branch).\n\n2. Analyzing        │
│ `opt`'s Log:\n\nThe log shows that the transformation happens in two steps:\n1. First iteration: `%ct = tail call noundef range(i32 0, 33) i32 @llvm.cttz.i32(i32 %x, i1 false)`\n2.      │
│ Second iteration: `%ct = tail call noundef range(i32 0, 33) i32 @llvm.cttz.i32(i32 %x, i1 true)`\n\nThe key insight is that the canonicalization of the icmp predicate assumes that all   │
│ users can be safely adapted, but this doesn't account for the fact that the cttz intrinsic's behavior depends on whether its input can be zero.\n\nThe `canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf`        │
│ function checks if users can be adapted to predicate inversion, and for a select instruction used as a condition, it returns true. However, this analysis doesn't consider that the       │
│ select's true/false operands might have different undefined behavior characteristics when the condition changes.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe root cause is in the                   │
│ `canonicalizeICmpPredicate` function. It calls `canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf` to check if all users can be adapted, but this function only considers the immediate users (like select,       │
│ branch, xor) and doesn't perform deeper analysis of what those users depend on.\n\nIn this case:\n- The icmp `ne` has one user: the select instruction\n- `canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf`     │
│ sees the select and thinks it's safe to invert\n- However, the select's true operand (`%ct`) comes from a cttz call that becomes poison when `%x = 0` if `is_zero_poison = true`\n- The   │
│ transformation pipeline later changes the cttz parameter, making the previously safe code unsafe\n\nThe fundamental issue is that `canonicalizeICmpPredicate` assumes that if immediate   │
│ users can be adapted, the transformation is safe. But when those users reference values that have conditional undefined behavior based on the same condition being inverted, this         │
│ assumption breaks down.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to prevent canonicalization when the icmp is comparing against zero and has users that might be affected by the zero  │
│ case. Specifically, we need to add a check in `canonicalizeICmpPredicate` to avoid canonicalizing icmp instructions that compare against zero when they have select users, because the    │
│ select's operands might have different behavior in the zero vs non-zero cases.\n\nHowever, looking more carefully at the actual problem: the real issue is that the cttz intrinsic's      │
│ `is_zero_poison` parameter is being changed from `false` to `true` in a later optimization. This change makes the cttz call produce poison when `%x = 0`, which wasn't the case           │
