│ re-examining the opt log: in iteration 1, after adding range metadata, it processes the icmp and canonicalizes it. Then in iteration 2, it changes the cttz parameter. But the Alive2     │
│ verification is checking the final result against the original source.\n\nThe core issue is that `canonicalizeICmpPredicate` is being too aggressive. When we have `icmp ne %x, 0` with a │
│ select user, and `%x` is used in a cttz with `is_zero_poison=false`, changing this to `icmp eq %x, 0` and swapping select operands is only safe if we guarantee that the cttz result is   │
│ not evaluated when `%x=0`. But LLVM's execution model means that both select operands are conceptually evaluated, so if the cttz becomes poison-producing for `%x=0`, we have UB.\n\nThe  │
│ proper fix is to not canonicalize icmp predicates when the comparison is against zero and there are select users, because the safety of the select operands may depend on the specific    │
│ condition.\n\nLooking at the current code in `canonicalizeICmpPredicate` at lines 7015-7017, we need to add a check to prevent canonicalization in this specific case.\n\n5.              │
│ Conclusion:\n\nThe fix is to add a guard in `canonicalizeICmpPredicate` to prevent canonicalization when the icmp compares against zero and has select users, as this can lead to         │
│ incorrect transformations when the select operands have conditional undefined behavior based on the same zero check."})                                                                   │
